- Collection = A dynamic list of data stored within your application. 

- Many different types, such as: lists (ordered elements), sets (unordered unique, non-duplicate elements), and maps (attaches an arbitrary key to an arbitrary value)

- Different collections store lists of data in ways suited to various types of tasks. 

- Collections contain certain shared methods (through interfaces), such as add, remove and size. 

- The two most important collections: ArrayList and HashMap 

/**********************************/ 

ARRAYLIST

- A dynamically-sized array of items that can have items added or removed. 

- Similar to an array, except with more methods available and with no fixed size.

ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<String>(); 


- Adding a new item to the list: 

list.add("Tool"); 

- Removing an item from the list: 

list.remove(1); 


Example: 

ArrayList<String> stringList = new ArrayList<String>(); 
  stringList.add("Item"); 

for(int i = 0; i<StringList.size(); i++) {
  String item = stringList.get(i);
  System.out.println("Item" + i + ": " + item);
}

stringList.remove(0);

System.out.println("ArrayList is " + stringList.size() + "items long!"); 


/*************************************/ 

HASHMAP

// A collection of values which are not kept in order, but are instead kept by "associating" each value to a 'key'. 

// Example:

HashMap<String, Integer> ratingMap = new HashMap<String, Integer>(); 
ratingMap.put("Dark Knight", 5);
ratingMap.put("Piranha 3D", 1);

/* The most important thing is to determine the correct 'key' and 'value'. 
The key should be the data you want to be able to access by, 
and the value should be the resulting attached data. 
Example: phone directory (key is the name, value is the number) */

// More Examples: 

// Store ratings for movies

HashMap<String, Integer> ratingMap = new HashMap<String, Integer>();
ratingMap.put("Dark Kngiht", 5);
ratingMap.put("Spiderman 2", 3);
ratingMap.put("Piranha 3D", 1);
System.out.println("Dark knight is rated a " + ratingMap.get("Dark Kngiht"));

// Phone numbers of people

HashMap<String, Integer> personMap = new HashMap<String, String>(); 
ratingMap.put("Bob", "415-123-4567");
ratingMap.put("Bill", "415-567-1235");
ratingMap.put("Joel", "650-740-2095");
System.out.println("Bob can be reached at " + ratingMap.get("Bob"));
